    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Key Takeaway}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        When a cone or a pyramid is cut horizontally, The top part will be 
        a smaller cone or pyramid, and the remaining part is called a frustum. 
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>\text{Volume of frustum}= \text{Volume of the big pyramid or cone}- \text{Volume of the small pyramid or cone}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        Which can be written as:
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>{\text{Volume}=\frac{1}{3}\pi R^2 H- \frac{1}{3}\pi r^2 h}</m>
    </p>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The figure below shows a frustum of a cone. Find its volume if the height of the cone is 
                <m>24\, \text{cm}</m>
            </p>
            <image width="50%">
            <latex-image label="Frustum-cone">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % Draw the bottom base (larger circle)
                    \draw [very thick](-2,0) arc (180:360:2 and 0.6)--cycle;
                    \draw[very thick,dashed] (2,0) arc (0:180:2 and 0.6);

                    % Draw the top base (smaller circle)
                    \draw[very thick]  (-1,3) arc (180:360:1 and 0.3)--cycle;
                    \draw[very thick] (1,3) arc (0:180:1 and 0.3);

                    % Draw the slant height lines for frustum
                    \draw[very thick,dashed]  (-2,0) -- (-1,3) --cycle;
                    \draw[very thick,dashed]  (2,0) -- (1,3)--cycle;


                    % Draw height lines
                    \draw[very thick,dashed] (0,0) -- (0,3); % Total height H
                    \draw[very thick,dashed] (0,0) -- (0,3); % Height of the frustum h

                    % Labeling the diagram
                
                    \node[above] at (0.5,2.9) {7 cm}; % Small radius
                    \node[below] at (-0.7,0) { 21 cm}; % Large radius
                    \node[left] at (0,1.5) {12cm};

                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
            </image>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The volume of the frustum can be calculated using the formula:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Volume of frustum} = \amp \text{Volume of the big cone} - \text{Volume of the small cone}</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp \frac{1}{3}\pi R^2 H- \frac{1}{3}\pi r^2 h </mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp \frac{1}{3} \times \frac{22}{7} \times 21^2 \times 24 - \frac{1}{3} \times \frac{22}{7} \times 7^2 \times 12</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp  11\,088-616</mrow>

                    
                    <mrow>= \amp 10472 \, \text{cm}^3</mrow>


                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore, the volume of the frustum is <m>{\color{blue}10472\, \text{cm}^3}</m>
            </p>

        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A lampshade in the form of a frustum is cut from a cone of height <m>40 \, \text{cm}</m>.
                The bottom diameter of the lampshade is <m>28 \, \text{cm}</m> and the top diameter is <m>14 \, \text{cm}</m>.
                Calculate the volume of the lampshade if its vertical height is <m>15 \, \text{cm}</m>. (Take <m>\pi= 3.142</m>).


            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The lampshade is in the form of frustum of a cone.
            </p>
            <p>
               <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The diamension of the lampshade is given as:
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <m>\text{Radius of the bottom base} = \frac{28}{2} = 14 \, \text{cm}</m>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <m>\text{Radius of the top base} = \frac{14}{2} = 7 \, \text{cm}</m>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <m>\text{Height of the frustum} = 15 \, \text{cm}</m>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <m>\text{Height of the whole cone} = 40 \, \text{cm}</m>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <m>\text{Height of the small cone} = 40 - 15 = 25 \, \text{cm}</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
               </ol>
            </p>
            <p>
                The volume of the frustum can be calculated using the formula:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Volume of lampshade} = \amp \text{Volume of the big cone} - \text{Volume of the small cone}</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp \frac{1}{3}\pi R^2 H- \frac{1}{3}\pi r^2 h </mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp \frac{1}{3} \times 3.142 \times 14^2 \times 40 - \frac{1}{3} \times 3.142 \times 7^2 \times 25</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp  \frac{1}{3} \times 3.142 \times (14^2 \times 40 - 7^2 \times 25)</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp \frac{1}{3} \times 3.142 \times (7840 - 1225)</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp \frac{1}{3} \times 3.142 \times 6615</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp 6928.11 \, \text{cm}^3</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore, the volume of the lampshade is <m>{\color{blue}6928.11\, \text{cm}^3}</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The diagram below is a pyramid. The upper part of the pyramid is cut off. 
                Calculate the volume of the frustum formed.
            </p>
